\begin_layout Standard
The map that truncates continued fractions is 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
h(x)=\frac{1}{x}-\left\lfloor \frac{1}{x}\right\rfloor \label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and is often called the Gauss Map.
 The Ruelle-Frobenius-Perron operator associated with the Gauss map is known
 as the Gauss-Kuzmin-Wirsing (GKW) operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

.
 It is the pushback of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, and as such, is a linear map between spaces of functions on the unit interval
 (Banach spaces).
 That is, given the vector space of functions from the closed unit interval
 to the real numbers 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\mathcal{F}=\left\{ f\,|\, f:\left[0,1\right]\to\mathbb{R}\right\} \]

\end_inset

then 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{L}_{h}$
\end_inset

 is a linear operator mapping 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

 .
 Given 
\begin_inset Formula $f\in\mathcal{F}$
\end_inset

, it is represented by 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}f\right](x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}\frac{1}{(n+x)^{2}}f\left(\frac{1}{n+x}\right)\label{eq:sum-form}\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This operator has not been 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

solved
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, in the sense that there is no known closed-form solution expressing its
 all of its eigenfunctions and eigenvectors.
 There is one classically known eigenvector, 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)=1/(1+x)$
\end_inset

, which corresponds to the unit eigenvalue; this solution was given by Gauss.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Aside from this, there is a large class of fractal, discontinuous-everywhere
 functions associated with eiegenvalue 1.
 The prototypical such solution is the derivative of the Minkowski Question
 Mark function 
\begin_inset Formula $?(x)$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}?^{\prime}\right](x)=?^{\prime}(x)\]

\end_inset

A proper construction for the everywhere-discontinuous function 
\begin_inset Formula $?^{\prime}$
\end_inset

, and the derivation of the above idetity, is given in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-mink2008"

\end_inset

, together with a construction of a class of other similar solutions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Relation to the Riemann Zeta
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Gauss map is connected to the Riemann Zeta by a Mellin Transform:
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{1}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}h(x)\, x^{s-1}dx\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

The Riemann zeta can be written under a change of variable as
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\zeta(s)=\frac{s}{s-1}-s\int_{0}^{1}dx\; x\left[\mathcal{L}_{h}x^{s-1}\right]\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

and thus it seems that a better understanding of GKW may shed light on the
 Riemann Hypothesis.
 Most immediately, simple manipulations lead to a representation for the
 Riemann zeta in terms of binomial coefficeints.
 This relation is explored in detail in 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-zeta2004,Fla06"

\end_inset

; it leads to criteria that are shown to be equivalent to the Riemann Hypothesis.
 The same development can be used to obtain Dirichlet L-functions, and generaliz
ations to other number-theoretic series, such as the totient series, or
 the Liouville series 
\begin_inset LatexCommand cite
key "Vep-norlund-2006"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

